<bibRefCitation author="Schultz" box="[523,795,153,179]" firstAuthor="Schultz" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" refId="ref199860" refString="Schultz, H. (2006) Sea Urchins - a guide to worldwide shallow-water species. 3 rd Edition. Heinke &amp; Peter Schultz Partner Scientific Publications, 484 pp." type="book" year="2006">Schultz (2006: 427–428</bibRefCitation>
, figs. 802–804).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="174.[151,1436,152,647]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,348,188,215]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Occurrence:</emphasis>
Northeast Atlantic and Mediterranean Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Tortonese" box="[836,1014,188,215]" firstAuthor="Tortonese" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" refId="ref202694" refString="Tortonese, E. (1965) Fauna D'Italia-Echinodermata. Edizioni Calderini, Bologna, 422 pp." type="book" year="1965">Tortonese 1965</bibRefCitation>
), from 
<collectingCountry box="[1095,1177,189,215]" name="Iceland" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Iceland</collectingCountry>
and Scandinavia along European and African coasts to 
<collectingCountry box="[522,611,225,251]" name="Senegal" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Senegal</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[628,833,224,251]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" refId="ref193260" refString="Mortensen, T. (1951 b) A Monograph of the Echinoidea. Vol. 2. Spatangoida II. Amphisternata II. Spatangidae, Loveniidae, Pericosmidae, Schizasteridae, Brissidae. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 593 pp." type="book" year="1951" yearSuffix="b">Mortensen 1951b</bibRefCitation>
); possibly also occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[1163,1295,225,251]" name="Cape Verde" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Cape Verde</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1354,1436,225,251]" name="Angola" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Angola</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[159,359,260,287]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" pagination="293 - 303" refId="ref193231" refString="Mortensen, T. (1951 a) Report on the Echinoidea collected by the &quot; Atlantide &quot; Expedition. Atlantide Report, 2, 293 - 303." type="journal article" year="1951" yearSuffix="a">Mortensen 1951a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="174.[151,1436,152,647]" box="[199,588,297,324]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,282,297,323]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Depth:</emphasis>
<quantity box="[289,388,297,323]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" unit="m" value="450.0" valueMax="900.0" valueMin="0.0">0–900 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Koehler" box="[402,576,297,324]" firstAuthor="Koehler" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" pagination="127 - 303" refId="ref185931" refString="Koehler, R. (1914 b) Echinoderma I: Asteroidea, ophiuroidea et Echnoidea. In: Michaelsen, W. (Ed.), Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Meeresfauna Westafrikas. 1 (2). L. Friederichsen &amp; Co., Hamburg, pp. 127 - 303." type="book chapter" year="1914" yearSuffix="b">Koehler 1914b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="174.[151,1436,152,647]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,332,359]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Habitat:</emphasis>
soft substrates, preferably on coarse sand or gravel, in which it lies wholly buried where it feeds on all sorts of bottom particles and organisms (
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[606,807,369,395]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" refId="ref192564" refString="Mortensen, T. (1927 a) Handbook of the echinoderms of the British Isles. Oxford University Press, viii + 471 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 6841" type="book" year="1927" yearSuffix="a">Mortensen 1927a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="174.[151,1436,152,647]" box="[199,875,405,431]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,357,405,431]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Larval stage:</emphasis>
planktotrophic (
<emphasis box="[544,563,406,431]" italics="true" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">c.</emphasis>
3 weeks; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[676,863,405,431]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref192355" refString="Mortensen, T. (1913) On the development of some British echinoderms. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom, 10 (1), 1 - 18. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / S 002531540000669 X" type="journal article" year="1913">Mortensen 1913</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="174.[151,1436,152,647]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,441,467]" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Remarks:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Agassiz" box="[323,493,441,467]" firstAuthor="Agassiz" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" pagination="1 - 321" refId="ref171039" refString="Agassiz, A. (1881) Report on the Echinoidea dredged by H. M. S. Challenger 1873 - 76. Report on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. Challenger, Zoology, 3, 1 - 321." type="journal article" year="1881">Agassiz (1881)</bibRefCitation>
identified the species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1776" box="[744,981,441,467]" class="Echinoidea" family="Spatangidae" genus="Spatangus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="purpureus">
<emphasis box="[744,981,441,467]" italics="true" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Spatangus purpureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
among the material collected by H.M.S. 
<emphasis box="[151,277,477,503]" italics="true" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Challenger</emphasis>
(sta 75: 
<geoCoordinate box="[382,481,477,503]" degrees="38" direction="north" minutes="37" orientation="latitude" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" precision="925" value="38.616665">38°37’N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[495,598,477,503]" degrees="28" direction="west" minutes="30" orientation="longitude" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" precision="925" value="-28.5">28°30’W</geoCoordinate>
, 
<quantity box="[612,728,476,503]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.285" metricValueMax="1.65" metricValueMin="0.9199999999999999" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" unit="m" value="128.5" valueMax="165.0" valueMin="92.0">92–165 m</quantity>
) in Azorean waters (no description was given). However, the existence of such specimen(s) could not be confirmed by H.L. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark" box="[870,1016,512,539]" firstAuthor="Clark" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" refId="ref177414" refString="Clark, H. L. (1925) A catalogue of the Recent sea urchins (Echinoidea) in the British Museum (Natural History). Trustees of the British Museum and Oxford University Press, London, 250 pp." type="book" year="1925">Clark (1925)</bibRefCitation>
or 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[1057,1277,512,539]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" refId="ref193260" refString="Mortensen, T. (1951 b) A Monograph of the Echinoidea. Vol. 2. Spatangoida II. Amphisternata II. Spatangidae, Loveniidae, Pericosmidae, Schizasteridae, Brissidae. C. A. Reitzel, Copenhagen, 593 pp." type="book" year="1951" yearSuffix="b">Mortensen (1951b)</bibRefCitation>
. Furthermore, the only other H.M.S. 
<emphasis box="[400,526,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Challenger</emphasis>
specimen identified by 
<bibRefCitation author="Agassiz" box="[790,960,549,575]" firstAuthor="Agassiz" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" pagination="1 - 321" refId="ref171039" refString="Agassiz, A. (1881) Report on the Echinoidea dredged by H. M. S. Challenger 1873 - 76. Report on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. Challenger, Zoology, 3, 1 - 321." type="journal article" year="1881">Agassiz (1881)</bibRefCitation>
as belonging to this species (off 
<collectingCountry box="[1324,1429,549,576]" name="Bermuda" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
) later proved to be a misidentification (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen" box="[633,822,585,611]" firstAuthor="Mortensen" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" pagination="1 - 200" refId="ref192287" refString="Mortensen, T. (1907) Echinoidea (Part 2). In: The Danish Ingolf-Expedition 1895 - 1896. 4 (2). Bianco Luno, Copenhagen, pp. 1 - 200." type="book chapter" year="1907">Mortensen 1907</bibRefCitation>
). Thus, the presence in the Azores of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Muller" authorityYear="1776" box="[1253,1397,585,611]" class="Echinoidea" family="Spatangidae" genus="Spatangus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spatangoida" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="purpureus">
<emphasis box="[1253,1267,585,611]" italics="true" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">S</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1283,1397,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="174" pageNumber="175">purpureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
remains unconfirmed.
</paragraph>
